</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36AC2D8FFA4FFDBE4AF241DC522F93B" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA4FFDBE4AF241DC12FF989" blockId="44.[189,324,1631,1657]" box="[189,324,1631,1657]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<heading id="D087263FFFA4FFDBE4AF241DC12FF989" bold="true" box="[189,324,1631,1657]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE4AF241DC12FF989" bold="true" box="[189,324,1631,1657]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA4FFDBE4AF24CCC522F93B" blockId="44.[189,1399,1677,1739]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
From Ancient Greek ‘ 
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE5D124CFC27CF958" box="[451,535,1677,1704]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">θάμνΟς</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘bush’, and ‘ 
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE72524CDC315F958" box="[823,894,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">πτΕρόν</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘wing’ or ‘feather’, to illustrate the appearance of the colonies of hydroids assignable to the present genus. The genus is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36AC2D8FFA4FFDAE4AF24B0C3DAFBFB" lastPageId="45" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA4FFDBE4AF24B0C144F8FC" blockId="44.[189,303,1778,1804]" box="[189,303,1778,1804]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<heading id="D087263FFFA4FFDBE4AF24B0C144F8FC" bold="true" box="[189,303,1778,1804]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE4AF24B0C144F8FC" bold="true" box="[189,303,1778,1804]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA4FFDAE4AF2563C325FE04" blockId="44.[189,1399,1825,2027]" lastBlockId="45.[189,1398,267,500]" lastPageId="45" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
The species under discussion herein (see below) shows obvious similarities with a hydroid described by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA4FFDBE4AF2506C1EDF8AE" author="Stechow E." box="[189,390,1860,1886]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="1 - 20" refId="ref26959" refString="Stechow E. 1923 c. Neue Hydroiden der Deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition, nebst Bemerkungen ʾ ber einige andre Formen. Zoologischer Anzeiger 56 (1 - 2): 1 - 20." type="journal article" year="1923">Stechow (1923c)</bibRefCitation>
under the basionym 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA4FFDBE6902506C310F8AE" authority="Allman, 1883" authorityName="Stechow" authorityYear="1923" box="[642,891,1860,1886]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Heteroplon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="valdiviae">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE6902506C310F8AE" box="[642,891,1860,1886]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Heteroplon valdiviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The latter forms large, ramified, fascicled colonies, giving rise irregularly, from the deeper tubes, to monosiphonic, 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA4FFDBE0522525C4D6F871" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1088,1213,1895,1921]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA4FFDBE0522525C4D6F871" box="[1088,1213,1895,1921]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like branchlets facing in all directions around the stem and/or its branches. The axes of branchlets are provided proximally with a prosegment, and occasionally with as many as four (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA4FFDBE01825EFC4C0F838" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[1034,1195,1965,1992]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" pagination="261 - 319" refId="ref25723" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1962. The Hydrozoa of the south and west coasts of South Africa. Part I. The Plumulariidae. Annals of the South African Museum 46 (11): 261 - 319." type="journal article" year="1962">Millard 1962</bibRefCitation>
); the prosegment bears a hydrotheca, its complement of nematothecae, and a pair of opposite cladial apophyses; the remainder of axis comprises a succession of hydrothecate internodes, each bearing a cladial apophysis lateral to a hydrotheca (proximalmost hydrotheca occasionally has a pair of opposite cladial apophyses); the apophyses are arranged alternately along the axis. With the exception of a short, proximal, athecate internode, followed by a nematothecate internode, the remainder of cladium is composed of a succession of thecate internodes separated by oblique nodes. Each hydrotheca, on both axes and cladia, is surrounded by 5 nematothecae: a mesial (well below its basis), a pair of laterals (of varied length and borne on short, conical apophyses), and a pair of axillar (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE6B3239BC32AFE04" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[673,833,473,500]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 513" refId="ref25765" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1975. Monograph on the Hydroida of southern Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 68: 1 - 513." type="journal article" year="1975">Millard 1975</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA5FFDAE4AF205BC4DFFD2F" blockId="45.[189,1399,537,736]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
Stechow’s (1923) species was sometimes assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE77B205BC38DFDC3" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[873,998,537,563]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE77B205BC38DFDC3" box="[873,998,537,563]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE052205BC48FFDC4" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[1088,1252,537,564]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="173 - 243" refId="ref25687" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1957. The Hydrozoa of False Bay, South Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 43 (4) (6): 173 - 243." type="journal article" year="1957">Millard 1957</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE0EB205BC55EFDC4" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[1273,1333,537,564]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="261 - 319" refId="ref25723" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1962. The Hydrozoa of the south and west coasts of South Africa. Part I. The Plumulariidae. Annals of the South African Museum 46 (11): 261 - 319." type="journal article" year="1962">1962</bibRefCitation>
) and sometimes to 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE572207EC1D5FDA6" authorityName="Millard" authorityYear="1962" box="[352,446,572,598]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Corhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE572207EC1D5FDA6" box="[352,446,572,598]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Corhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE5DF207EC207FDA6" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[461,620,571,598]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 513" refId="ref25765" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1975. Monograph on the Hydroida of southern Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 68: 1 - 513." type="journal article" year="1975">Millard 1975</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE66A207EC358FDA6" author="Schuchert P." box="[632,819,572,598]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref26517" refString="Schuchert P. 1997. Review of the family Halopterididae. Zoologische Verhandelingen, Leiden 309: 1 - 162. Available from https: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 149017 [accessed 12 Aug. 2020]." type="journal article" year="1997">Schuchert 1997</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE755207EC39EFDA6" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[839,1013,571,598]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 513" refId="ref25765" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1975. Monograph on the Hydroida of southern Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 68: 1 - 513." type="journal article" year="1975">Millard (1975)</bibRefCitation>
argued that a genus allocation to 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE4AF201CC170FD88" authorityName="Millard" authorityYear="1962" box="[189,283,606,632]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Corhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE4AF201CC170FD88" box="[189,283,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Corhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was more opportune, for the “appearance of the colony is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE098201CC56AFD88" authorityName="Vervoort &amp; Watson" authorityYear="2003" baseAuthorityName="Ritchie" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[1162,1281,606,632]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Corhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="scotiae">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE098201CC56AFD88" box="[1162,1281,606,632]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">C. scotiae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differing from it in the fact that the diverging tubes of the stem form sub-branches instead of hydrocladia”. The diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE54A20E0C1DDFD4C" authorityName="Millard" authorityYear="1962" box="[344,438,674,700]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Corhiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE54A20E0C1DDFD4C" box="[344,438,674,700]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Corhiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was modified accordingly, so as to include species with “branches […] bearing cauline hydrothecae and pinnately arranged hydrocladia”, as well (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE7D92087C4C3FD2F" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[971,1192,709,736]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 513" refId="ref25765" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1975. Monograph on the Hydroida of southern Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 68: 1 - 513." type="journal article" year="1975">Millard 1975: 334</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA5FFDAE4AF2144C120FC58" blockId="45.[189,1399,773,937]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
However, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE52A2147C190FCD0" author="Millard N. A. H." box="[312,507,773,800]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="1 - 513" refId="ref25765" refString="Millard N. A. H. 1975. Monograph on the Hydroida of southern Africa. Annals of the South African Museum 68: 1 - 513." type="journal article" year="1975">Millard’s (1975)</bibRefCitation>
opinion that unites into a single genus species whose fascicled stems and, if present, branches give rise to either 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE690216AC36AFCB2" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[642,769,808,834]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Antennella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE690216AC36AFCB2" box="[642,769,808,834]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Antennella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like hydrocladia or 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE7E0216AC404FCB2" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1010,1135,808,834]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE7E0216AC404FCB2" box="[1010,1135,808,834]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like branchlets, is not shared here. If this principle is applied to the genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE75C2108C3A6FC94" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[846,973,842,868]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Antennella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE75C2108C3A6FC94" box="[846,973,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Antennella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE01C2108C4E0FC94" authorityName="Allman" authorityYear="1877" box="[1038,1163,842,868]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Halopteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE01C2108C4E0FC94" box="[1038,1163,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Halopteris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, they must also be regarded as congeneric, although increasing evidence demonstrates that both are polyphyletic (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE1ECA2FFA5FFDAE134212EC154FC58" author="Moura C. &amp; Lessios H. &amp; Cortes J. &amp; Nizinski M. S. &amp; Reed J. &amp; Santos R. S. &amp; Collins A. G." pageId="45" pageNumber="46" pagination="17986" refId="ref25878" refString="Moura C., Lessios H., Cortes J., Nizinski M. S., Reed J., Santos R. S. &amp; Collins A. G. 2018. Hundreds of genetic barcodes of the species-rich hydroid superfamily Plumularioidea (Cnidaria, Medusozoa) provide a guide toward more reliable taxonomy. Scientific Reports 8: 17986. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / s 41598 - 018 - 35528 - 8" type="journal article" year="2018">
Moura 
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE4AF21CDC09BFC58" box="[189,240,910,936]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCF9153FFA5FFDAE4AF218DC3DAFBFB" blockId="45.[189,1399,975,1036]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
The new genus comprises presently two species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE709218DC566FC19" authority="(Stechow, 1923)" baseAuthorityName="Stechow" baseAuthorityYear="1923" box="[795,1293,975,1001]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Thamnopteros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="valdiviae">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE709218DC450FC19" box="[795,1083,975,1001]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Thamnopteros valdiviae</emphasis>
(Stechow, 1923)
</taxonomicName>
, its 
<typeStatus id="54CB2FF1FFA5FFDAE156218DC51CFC19" box="[1348,1399,975,1001]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
species, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C70EAD0FFA5FFDAE54021B0C24DFBFB" authority="Galea" authorityName="Galea" authorityYear="2020" box="[338,550,1009,1035]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Halopterididae" genus="Thamnopteros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leptothecata" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="uniserius" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9044D41FFA5FFDAE54021B0C1B0FBFB" box="[338,475,1010,1035]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">T. uniserius</emphasis>
Galea
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A237F03AFFA5FFDAE63F21B0C28BFBFC" box="[557,736,1010,1036]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, described below.
</paragraph>
